nib.text:
Authorities have issued dispersal orders after hundreds of demonstrators gathered outside of Brooklyn Center Police Department headquarters Tuesday night.

It is the third night of protests since Daunte Wright was fatally shot by a former Brooklyn Center police officer during a traffic stop.

Earlier in the evening, a Justice for Daunte Wright rally was held. The group marched to the FBI building in Brooklyn Center and then back to the police department. Participants carried banners and chanted while they marched. 

Citizen users shared video along the route. 

The city of Brooklyn Center issued a curfew that will go into effect at 10 p.m.

-MY7ij3KDd6l4JJxs0Cq.text: Police are monitoring several hundred protesters demonstrating outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department.

-MY7itdmgyXPtIIMdJWP.text: National Guard personnel report the protesters have begun throwing hazardous objects.

nib.text:
Demonstrators gathered outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department Monday night, one day after Daunte Wright was shot and killed by police during a traffic stop.

A 7 p.m. curfew went into effect in Hennepin County and the surrounding counties of Anoka, Dakota, and Ramsey.

Hundreds of people remained after curfew outside of the police building, which was fenced off, despite multiple dispersal orders from law enforcement. 

Video from local media and those in the crowd showed law enforcement deploying tear gas and flash-bang canisters.

Officers warned that curfew violations would result in misdemeanor charges for anyone arrested.

In a midnight press conference, officials said that police made about 40 arrests ranging from curfew violation to riotous behavior. 

According to officials, a several officers suffered minor injuries due to thrown debris. 

Officials said that they were unaware of any injuries to protesters Monday night. 

Minneapolis Police officials said that five businesses in Minneapolis were burglarized, including a liquor store, a Target Express, a tobacco store, an AutoZone and a shoe store.

nib.text:
Minneapolis, St. Paul, and several area cities are under curfew starting at 10 p.m. Tuesday until 6 a.m. Wednesday. 

According to local officials, Brooklyn Center, Columbia Heights, Crystal, Maple Grove, and Robbinsdale will also be under curfew through Wednesday morning. 

The curfew includes exemptions for credentialed press, law enforcement, emergency responders, those traveling to and from work, and community patrols. A full list is available [here](https://www.minneapolismn.gov/news/2021/april/curfew-april-13/).

The curfew comes after Minneapolis Mayor Jacob Frey and St. Paul Mayor Melvin Carter declared States of Emergency following the fatal shooting of Daunte Wright in Brooklyn Center on Sunday, April 11th.

Earlier on Tuesday, Gov. Tim Walz lifted the state-imposed curfews in Hennepin, Ramsey, Dakota, and Anoka counties but said local jurisdictions were still able to impose their own curfews.
